---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Wrapper from "@/components/fundations/containers/Wrapper.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <Wrapper variant="standard" class="py-8 lg:py-12">
    <header>
      <h1
        class="text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-bold leading-[0.9] tracking-tighter uppercase"
      >
        Just fucking<br />use Astro
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm mt-4 max-w-md text-black/60 dark:text-white/60">
        (Unless you're building an actual app, you sweet, fragile,
        over-engineering dipshit motherfucker.)
      </p>
    </header>

    <div
      class="mt-12 grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
    >
      <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50">author</p>
      <p>
        <a
          href="https://michaelandreuzza.com/"
          class="underline hover:no-underline">Michael Andreuzza</a
        >
        — the motherfucker who made this rant possible when he had nothing to do.
      </p>

      <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6 lg:mt-8">summary</p>
      <p class="mt-6 lg:mt-8">
        <strong>Most sites are content plus a few interactive bits.</strong>
        If you're shipping a full SPA for a fucking marketing site, you're not "modern."
        You're a goddamn irresponsible jackass, lazy as shit with architecture, and
        actively making the web a worse fucking shithole for everyone. Fuck you.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          What is this?
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            This is a public service announcement for braindead dumbass
            motherfucking developers still building websites like it's 2012 <em
              >or</em
            > 2022 and acting proud of it like they invented sliced fucking bread,
            you absolute morons.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">You've got two equally stupid fucking religions:</p>
          <p class="mt-2">
            <strong>"No frameworks ever."</strong> Congrats, you fucking idiot, you
            rebuilt a worse CMS with worse routing, worse builds, and zero goddamn
            guardrails. Your shitty site is one junior dev away from collapsing into
            an unreadable pile of HTML sadness.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2">
            <strong>"SPA for everything."</strong> Congrats, you pretentious motherfucker,
            you shipped hundreds of kilobytes of JavaScript bullshit to render a
            headline, three buttons, and your fragile fucking ego.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">the web is</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          fucking pages, fucking content, fucking navigation, fucking forms, a
          couple fucking interactive widgets — not a goddamn desktop application
          duct-taped into a browser tab with delusions of grandeur.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          Why not pure HTML?
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            Because "pure HTML" at scale is a fucking lie you tell yourself
            until the site hits page 37 and everything quietly catches fire
            around you like your pathetic career.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">Then this shit happens:</p>
          <p class="mt-1">— you copy and paste layouts like it's 2009</p>
          <p>— your "tiny bit of JS" becomes a cursed spaghetti altar</p>
          <p>— content turns into an untyped clusterfuck</p>
          <p>
            — the build process becomes duct tape, shell scripts, and prayers
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">astro gives you</p>
        <div class="mt-6">
          <p>— components without joining a JS framework cult</p>
          <p>— actual layouts instead of copy-paste hell</p>
          <p>— sane file-based routing</p>
          <p>— typed content collections</p>
          <p>— React, Vue, Svelte only when needed</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">december 2025</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          <strong>Astro ships zero client-side JavaScript by default.</strong> No
          tricks. No asterisks. No bullshit hydration tax. Nothing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          Why not React?
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            Because React is great. <strong>For apps, dipshit.</strong>
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            Most websites are not fucking apps, no matter how much you
            desperately want them to be.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">if your site is</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          marketing pages, docs, a blog, landing pages, ecommerce front — then
          shipping a full SPA is like bringing a forklift to carry a sandwich,
          then congratulating yourself for "scalability."
        </p>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">philosophy</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          Astro is the "HTML-first, JS-when-needed" workflow that SPA developers <em
            >say</em
          > they follow and then immediately ignore like the lying bastards they
          are.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          Islands
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            <strong
              >Your page is static by default. Interactivity is the exception,
              not the rule.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            Carousel? Island. Pricing toggle? Island. Search? Island.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            Everything else stays server-rendered, boring, fast, and quiet —
            like a well-behaved website that respects its users.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">that means</p>
        <div class="mt-6">
          <p>— dramatically less JavaScript shipped</p>
          <p>— fewer hydration nightmares at 3am</p>
          <p>— fewer "why did this re-render?" panic attacks</p>
          <p>— a page that works immediately</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">rule</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          You don't need to hydrate the fucking world. You need to hydrate the <em
            >one</em
          > damn widget and leave the rest alone.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          When to use
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>— your site is mostly content with some UI sprinkled on top</p>
          <p>— SEO actually matters</p>
          <p>— you want components without the SPA performance tax</p>
          <p>— you want React or Svelte only where it makes sense</p>
          <p>— your interactivity is localized, not infecting the whole page</p>
          <p>— you want a site that doesn't become a nightmare at 50+ pages</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">note</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          If you're thinking "but I can do that with vanilla JS", yes, and you
          can also eat soup with a fork. Stop pretending that suffering equals
          skill.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          When NOT to use
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>— a heavy client-side app with shared state everywhere</p>
          <p>— real-time collaborative tools</p>
          <p>— interfaces where literally everything is interactive</p>
          <p>— complex offline-first behavior</p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">instead use</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          React/Next, SvelteKit, Remix, whatever works. Astro is for sites that
          behave like websites, with selective "app" bullshit only where it
          belongs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          About bloat
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            If you use Astro correctly, it <strong
              >does not ship what you don't use</strong
            >. That's the whole point, genius.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            If your Astro site ships 500KB of JavaScript, congratulations: you
            ignored the entire philosophy and rebuilt a SPA like a complete
            idiot.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            That's not Astro's fault. That's you being addicted to unnecessary
            complexity like it's heroin.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-tight lg:text-base lg:font-normal lg:normal-case lg:text-black/50 lg:dark:text-white/50"
        >
          The real problem
        </h2>
        <div>
          <p>
            The real problem is developers who can't evaluate the job and treat
            tool choice like a personality trait or a religion.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">
          pick based on reality
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6">
          <p>
            — Content-heavy with selective interactivity? <strong>Astro.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p>
            — Highly interactive, stateful client app? <strong
              >React/Next/whatever.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p>
            — Somewhere in between? <strong
              >Think for five goddamn seconds.</strong
            >
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50 mt-6">advice</p>
        <p class="mt-6">
          Stop treating tools like identity. It's engineering. Act like a
          professional.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-16">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold leading-[0.9] tracking-tighter uppercase"
      >
        Now go ship<br />something fast
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm mt-4 max-w-lg">
        If you're building a mostly-content website and still reaching for a
        full SPA: you're not being advanced. You're being lazy, insecure, and
        shit at trade-offs. Go build something that loads fast, ships less
        JavaScript, and doesn't actively hate your users.
      </p>
    </section>

    <footer class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-black/10 dark:border-white/10">
      <div
        class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[200px_1fr] gap-x-12 gap-y-1 text-sm leading-relaxed"
      >
        <p class="text-black/50 dark:text-white/50">inspirations</p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8 gap-y-1">
          <a
            href="https://motherfuckingwebsite.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">motherfuckingwebsite.com</a
          >
          <a
            href="https://justfuckingusetailwind.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">justfuckingusetailwind.com</a
          >
          <a
            href="https://justfuckingusehttp.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">justfuckingusehttp.com</a
          >
          <a
            href="https://justfuckingusereact.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">justfuckingusereact.com</a
          >
          <a
            href="https://justfuckingusecss.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">justfuckingusecss.com</a
          >
          <a
            href="https://www.justfuckinguserails.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="hover:underline">justfuckinguserails.com</a
          >
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-black/40 dark:text-white/40 mt-8">
        Now stop reading and go fucking build something.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </Wrapper>
</BaseLayout>
